HANTAVIRUS - AMERICAS (65): ARGENTINA (CHUBUT) FATAL, SUSPECTED
***************************************************************
A ProMED-mail post
http://www.promedmail.org
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
http://www.isid.org

[1]
Date: Mon 3 Dec 2018
Source: El Patagonico [in Spanish trans. Mod.TY, edited]
https://www.elpatagonico.com/fallecio-una-nina-14-anos-un-cuadro-sospechoso-hantavirus-n5003058


Medical personnel of the Epuyen Hospital held a press conference in order to answer questions about the death of a 14-year-old girl who could have been infected by [a] hantavirus. They stated that the girl was admitted with digestive problems and after some hours she was considered a suspected case of [a] hantavirus [infection]. However, this has not been confirmed.

Because of this, it was indicated that in Chubut province there is just one confirmed case of [a] hantavirus [infection] that was detected on 13 Nov [2018]. This was a case of a man who resided in an agricultural [chacras] area.

Nevertheless, there are another suspected 5 cases. Now the technical team has to identify the common factors that could determine the source of the infection.

Of these suspected cases, 3 are patients in intensive therapy. The others are in ambulatory care.

"We can say that they are not of the same nuclear family, are not from urban areas, rather from rural ones, but tomorrow we are going to be in the Epuyen locality to carry out a survey.

Recommendations for residents of the mountains
----------------------------------------------
The Ministry of Health recommends: camp in a sunny area, free of weeds and trash where no rodent nests are found," as well as "do not go into the forest, into places that have brush and where there are no warning signs stating that it is a safe area."

For rural area residents: "precautionary measures must be taken when carrying out tasks in rural areas," and in that sense, "dampen down areas before cleaning and wear eye, nose, and mouth protection in order to not breathe rodent excrements or urine that, with the passage of time become desiccated and produce dust that can be easily breathed, which is the mechanism by which hantaviruses infection occurs."

"If the area has been closed for considerable time, first ventilate it and later clean it."

--
