******
[2]
Date: Mon 3 Dec 2018 11:29 ART
Source: Tiempo Sur [in Spanish, trans. Mod.TY, edited]
https://www.tiemposur.com.ar/nota/161815-alerta-por-cinco-casos-sospechosos-de-hantavirus-entre-ellos-uno-fatal


The [Epuyen] community in Chubut [province] is shocked about the death of a 14-year-old girl, whose demise could be due to [a] hantavirus [infection]. Meanwhile, another 4 people are receiving [medical] attention in Esquel. One of these is in intensive care.

In Epuyen, 5 cases, one of them fatal, are suspected to have hantavirus [infections]. The mayor of the locality, Antonio Reato, stated that confirmation is awaited for the samples sent to the Carlos Malbran Institute.

The dead child was 14 years old; the other 4 cases are attended in Esquel. One of the patients being treated is a municipal employee.

Mayor Reato spoke with the Minister of Health, Adrian Pizzi, and coordinated the dispatch of Zoonoses personnel to conduct a survey of the area where the residents of Epuyen with suspected hantavirus infections live.

"This is a sad day for us due to the girl who died. There is no definite diagnosis. The samples are sent to Buenos Aires, but all was delayed because there were flights during the [G20 Buenos Aires summit, 30 Nov-1 Dec 2018]," Reato stated.

"There are 4 suspected cases, in addition to the 14-year-old girl," he continued. "The hospitalized individuals are in stable condition. There is a municipal employee in intensive case, and we hope that he will leave it in coming days."

"Hantavirus disease is an emergent zoonoses transmitted to humans by rodents infected with that virus, mainly in suburban and rural environments, in peridomestic situations, or in closed places like sheds or storage buildings. However, it has been seen in periurban and domestic areas where there are invasions of rodents seeking food or refuge.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail from HealthMap Alerts
<promed@promedmail.org>

[These reports do not indicate which hantavirus might be responsible for these 5 suspected cases. Esquel is located in the Andes mountains, and the virus most likely involved is Andes hantavirus, which is endemic in the southern Andes. This is the beginning of the summer season, when cases of hantavirus infection occur. The patients likely came into contact with areas inhabited by the rodent reservoir of the virus in the region.

Andes virus is rarely transmitted directly person to person and only through close physical contact, usually within the family. The most common source of the infection is the long-tailed pygmy rice rat.

Images of the long-tailed pygmy rice rat (_Oligoryzomys longicaudatus_), the Sigmodontine rodent host of Andes hantavirus, can be seen at https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Oligoryzomys_longicaudatus#/media/File:Raton_colilarga.jpg. - Mod.TY

